05133nam a22008535i 9780674736269DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20152015mau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013941909  a(OCoLC)1029825473  a(OCoLC)1032677974  a(OCoLC)1037981840  a(OCoLC)1041979842  a(OCoLC)1046615579  a(OCoLC)1047024803  a(OCoLC)979723450  a97806747362697 a10.4159/harvard.97806747362692doi  a(DE-B1597)427932  a(OCoLC)897599014  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aUA840 7aHIS0270002bisacsh04a322/.509542231 aWilkinson, Steven I., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aArmy and Nation :bThe Military and Indian Democracy since Independence /cSteven I. Wilkinson. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (262 p.) :b16 line illustrations, 16 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction: Army and Nation -- t1. Divide and Rule -- t2. War and Partition -- t3. Protecting the New Democracy -- t4. From 1962 to Bluestar -- t5. Army and Nation Today -- t6. The Path Not Taken: Pakistan 1947– 1977 -- tConclusion: Army and Nation -- tAppendix: Data on the Changing Composition of the Indian Military since 1930 -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt Indian independence in 1947, the country’s founders worried that the army India inherited— conservative and dominated by officers and troops drawn disproportionately from a few “martial” groups—posed a real threat to democracy. They also saw the structure of the army, with its recruitment on the basis of caste and religion, as incompatible with their hopes for a new secular nation. India has successfully preserved its democracy, however, unlike many other colonial states that inherited imperial “divide and rule” armies, and unlike its neighbor Pakistan, which inherited part of the same Indian army in 1947. As Steven I. Wilkinson shows, the puzzle of how this happened is even more surprising when we realize that the Indian Army has kept, and even expanded, many of its traditional “martial class” units, despite promising at independence to gradually phase them out. Army and Nation draws on uniquely comprehensive data to explore how and why India has succeeded in keeping the military out of politics, when so many other countries have failed. It uncovers the command and control strategies, the careful ethnic balancing, and the political, foreign policy, and strategic decisions that have made the army safe for Indian democracy. Wilkinson goes further to ask whether, in a rapidly changing society, these structures will survive the current national conflicts over caste and regional representation in New Delhi, as well as India’s external and strategic challenges.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aCivil-military relations -- India -- History. 0aCivil-military relationszIndiaxHistory. 0aIndia -- Military policy -- History. 0aIndia -- Politics and government -- 1947-. 0aIndia. -- Army -- History. 7aHISTORY / Military / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2015z9783110438635oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106659010 cprintz978067472880640uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067473626940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674736269423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674736269/original  a978-3-11-066590-1  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-201